      "content": "Certainly! A deadlock in the transaction pool is akin to a situation where two goblins, each holding a key to a treasure chest, are standing at a crossroads. Goblin A has the key to Goblin B's chest, and Goblin B has the key to Goblin A's chest. Neither goblin can move forward because they each need the other's key to progress. In your system, this deadlock occurs when two or more processes are waiting for each other to release locks on resources, causing a standstill.\n\nTo resolve this goblin standoff and prevent deadlocks during traffic spikes, consider the following strategies:\n\n1. **Lock Ordering**: Establish a consistent order in which locks are acquired. By ensuring that all processes request locks in the same order, you can prevent the circular wait condition that leads to deadlocks.\n\n2. **Timeouts**: Implement timeouts for lock acquisition. If a process cannot acquire a lock within a certain timeframe, it should release any locks it currently holds and retry after a random delay. This can help break the deadlock by forcing one of the processes to back off and release its locks.\n\n3. **Deadlock Detection and Resolution**: Implement a mechanism to detect deadlocks when they occur",
